I agree.<br><br>
The point I would like you to consider is: besides all the grieves about that war, Americans should know that you were fighting against an evil in Vietnam. An evil that might have won a lot of support at that time, but later showed its teeth toward its own people as well as people in neighboring countries. Even though some of  you might not have held a higher standard in fighting that war—regarding My Lai, etc.--, you had at least given those that  didn’t want to live a Communist life a chance.  And probably, you would be hailed as &quot;liberators&quot; if you fight that war today.<br><br>
I have thought a lot about those fighters on the other side these days. They must have believed that their sacrifices would help build up a better world for their children. But, instead, we are now witnessing the collapse of their world and everything.  What the sadness they must have felt now, if ever they had survived all those &quot;movements&quot; and &quot;re-educations&quot;.  Thinking about those souls wandering for a meaning for their lives makes me blue!<br>

